High-Level Design: Automated Portfolio Allocation System

1. Architectural Overview
The system is designed as a microservices-based application orchestrated via Docker Compose in a Swarm environment.
It strictly separates user-facing interaction (Online Stage) from the automated machine learning lifecycle (Offline Stage).

2. System Components & Design Rationale

 A. Online Stage (User Interaction & Inference)
* Reverse Proxy (Security): Acts as the single entry point, providing SSL/TLS termination to encrypt data in transit.
* Frontend (Streamlit): An independent UI block for non-technical users to view portfolio recommendations.
It features a dedicated Pipeline Visualization screen to display system health and DAG status.
* Backend (FastAPI): A RESTful API that handles business logic and serves model predictions. 
It is loosely coupled from the UI, communicating solely via HTTP requests.
* Database (PostgreSQL/SQLite): Stores application state, user inputs, and historical portfolio snapshots.

 B. Offline Stage (ML Lifecycle & Automation)
* Orchestrator (Apache Airflow): Automates the end-to-end pipeline, including data ingestion (`yfinance`), preprocessing, and feature engineering.
* Data & Model Versioning (DVC): Tracks data artifacts and model weights to ensure 100% reproducibility across experiments.
* Experiment Tracking (MLflow): Interlaced with Airflow to log hyperparameters, metrics (Sharpe Ratio), and artifacts.

 C. Monitoring & Maintenance (The Feedback Loop)
* Instrumentation (Prometheus): Scrapes metrics from the Backend and Airflow to monitor inference latency and system health[cite: 71, 72].
* Visualization (Grafana): Provides Near Real-Time (NRT) dashboards for data drift and performance tracking[cite: 74, 162].
* Automated Retraining: Uses Alertmanager to trigger a webhook back to Airflow, initiating a retraining DAG if data drift is detected[cite: 161, 164, 165].



 3. Data & Communication Flow
1.  Ingestion: Airflow pulls market data $\rightarrow$ Validates schema $\rightarrow$ Versions with DVC[cite: 118, 122].
2.  Training: Airflow triggers XGBoost training $\rightarrow$ Logs to MLflow $\rightarrow$ Registers the best model[cite: 137, 142, 177].
3.  Deployment: GitHub Actions builds a Docker image with the latest model $\rightarrow$ Deploys to the Backend[cite: 106, 152].
4.  Inference: Frontend requests weights $\rightarrow$ Backend fetches model from MLflow Registry $\rightarrow$ Returns allocation[cite: 76, 153].
5.  Monitoring: Prometheus detects drift $\rightarrow$ Alertmanager signals Airflow $\rightarrow$ Pipeline restarts[cite: 160, 161].



 4. Design Principles Adhered To
* Loose Coupling: Frontend and Backend are independent software blocks.
* Environment Parity: Docker ensures identical dev/test/prod environments.
* Automation: All stages from ingestion to monitoring are automated.
